Yes, sensible. The main gain is that `toggleSplitPoint` currently coordinates three separate state updates — that's the fragility. A single `Map<number, { name: string; folderOverride?: string }>` keyed by `firstPage` becomes the source of truth, and `splitPoints` becomes derived from it (`new Set([...outputFiles.keys()].filter(k => k > 1).map(k => k - 1))`).

The tradeoff: `ThumbnailPanel` receives `splitPoints` today as a plain `Set` for gap rendering — you'd either derive it before passing down (simple) or change the prop to `outputFiles` and derive inside (more invasive). Deriving at the call site is the lighter path.

The hook interface would be something like:

```typescript
const files = useOutputFiles()
// files.toggle(afterPage, prefillName, prefillCursorPos)
// files.setName(firstPage, name)
// files.setFolderOverride(firstPage, folder)
// files.reset(firstPageName)
// files.splitPoints  ← derived Set<number>
// files.all          ← Map<number, OutputFile>
```

Worth doing — want me to go ahead?

